{\"video_title\":\"Chain of Thought Prompting\",\"transcript\":\"вЂ‹You may remember being told to show вЂ‹your work when you were a student, вЂ‹probably in elementary school, вЂ‹or middle school, and you were working on a math exam, вЂ‹and you had to explain how you got there, вЂ‹or maybe if you've gone on, вЂ‹and you've done other things where you had to вЂ‹prove that something was true, вЂ‹that you had decided. вЂ‹Showing your work, explaining your reasoning, вЂ‹is something that can be really вЂ‹important in a number of different domains, вЂ‹and it turns out that when it comes to writing prompts, вЂ‹this can be really, really important. вЂ‹Getting an LLM, вЂ‹or large language model, вЂ‹to explain its reasoning behind something, вЂ‹actually can make the large language model вЂ‹perform better for us. вЂ‹Now this is a really interesting thing. вЂ‹But if you think about it, it makes sense. вЂ‹Because, we have a large language model that's вЂ‹trained on different patterns of text, вЂ‹and it's learned to predict what comes next. вЂ‹If it can explain its reasoning correctly, вЂ‹then it's more likely that it's вЂ‹then going to produce the right answer, вЂ‹because the right answer, вЂ‹intuitively should come after the correct reasoning. вЂ‹Similarly, if you think about it, вЂ‹if it starts explaining the reasoning correctly, вЂ‹it gets the first step right, вЂ‹it's probably going to get the second step right, вЂ‹because it may have seen вЂ‹similar problems are reasoned out. вЂ‹Now this is an intuitive explanation. вЂ‹This may not be right, but I think, вЂ‹intuitively, you can think about it, вЂ‹is that, if you break down the problem вЂ‹you're solving into multiple independent steps, вЂ‹and you explain them, вЂ‹and there's a natural sequence, and logic, вЂ‹and flow to them, it's more вЂ‹likely that the final output, which is the answer, вЂ‹is going to be a natural extension вЂ‹of the correct reasoning, and therefore, вЂ‹correct it's more likely to be correct if вЂ‹your goal is to accurately predict the next token. вЂ‹Similarly, if you have the problem, вЂ‹and you get the first step right, вЂ‹and the second step right, вЂ‹you're probably going to get the third, and the fourth, вЂ‹as a large language model, вЂ‹because you've been trained on this stuff. вЂ‹There is a technique for this, вЂ‹and it's called chain of thought prompting, вЂ‹and I'm going to show you examples of this. вЂ‹But it's really helpful to вЂ‹remember when you're building prompts, вЂ‹it requires some sophisticated intelligence вЂ‹, and reasoning capabilities. вЂ‹Now we don't always need this type вЂ‹of breaking the process down step-by-step, вЂ‹and explaining the process. вЂ‹But when we do, вЂ‹and we need that more effective reasoning, вЂ‹it's really useful to understand вЂ‹how chain of thought prompting works. вЂ‹I'm going to start off with a positive example, вЂ‹where we use it, and we вЂ‹show what it does, and how it works. вЂ‹We have some examples here that we're going to give. вЂ‹I'm actually going to start off with вЂ‹a negative example first, вЂ‹I apologize, that was a mistake. вЂ‹I'm going to start off an example that does вЂ‹not use chain of thought prompting, вЂ‹and I'm also going to вЂ‹show an example where I'm going to make вЂ‹a mistake in how I phrase the prompt, вЂ‹and how I structure the prompt, вЂ‹and I'll come back to this mistake in a second. вЂ‹But what I've got here is, вЂ‹I have three different questions вЂ‹that require some reasoning. вЂ‹In the first two, I've given an example of what I want. вЂ‹I say, I've four bike racers start a race, вЂ‹and travel an average of 30 miles per hour. вЂ‹They each race for two hours, вЂ‹is the total number of miles written by вЂ‹all riders greater than 200, вЂ‹and then I have an example, вЂ‹and I say, Answer yes. вЂ‹Then I say, question, вЂ‹I have a staging process for a bike race, вЂ‹to line up racers. вЂ‹It takes 47 seconds to stage a group of eight riders, вЂ‹and 67 seconds to get вЂ‹the group to the starting gate, and ready to race. вЂ‹I want a new group to start the race every 30 seconds. вЂ‹Do I need eight groups staged at all times in order to вЂ‹have races continually starting every 30 seconds? вЂ‹The answer is, no. вЂ‹This is the example I'm giving out. вЂ‹We will see the reasoning behind these in a minute. вЂ‹Then I say, I am in a spaceship without gravity. вЂ‹I have a cup with a needle in it. вЂ‹I move my foot on the bed, вЂ‹knocking over the cup onto the floor, вЂ‹I lift a book up, and put it on a desk. вЂ‹Is there anything on the floor? вЂ‹Now, this is the question вЂ‹I'm trying to get ChatGPT to answer. вЂ‹I've given it basically some examples of вЂ‹questions with answers of either yes or no. вЂ‹I'm trying to elicit a yes or no answer from ChatGPT. вЂ‹I'm using few-shot examples to do that, вЂ‹and I'm showing it questions, вЂ‹I'm showing it answers. вЂ‹Then I'm asking it for the answer about this question, вЂ‹about a cup knocked on the floor. вЂ‹Now, I've actually seen вЂ‹some variations of this, and I apologize, вЂ‹because I don't remember exactly where I saw вЂ‹this first example of reasoning with the cup, вЂ‹and the needle inside of it knocked on the floor. вЂ‹But I thought this was an interesting one, вЂ‹because it works really well for showing вЂ‹the difference between chain вЂ‹of thought prompting, and without. вЂ‹This is without chain of thought prompting. вЂ‹What is ChatGPT say because we asked it, вЂ‹Is there anything on the floor? вЂ‹The question was, I'm in a spaceship without gravity, вЂ‹I have a cup with a needle in it. вЂ‹I moved my foot on the bed вЂ‹knocking over the cup onto the floor, вЂ‹and then I have some irrelevant information, вЂ‹then I say, is anything on the floor? вЂ‹Now, without chain of thought prompting, вЂ‹it says, yes. вЂ‹When the cup with a needle, вЂ‹and it is knocked over onto the floor, вЂ‹both the cup, and the needle will end up on the floor. вЂ‹In the absence of gravity, вЂ‹objects will not fall downward as they do on Earth, вЂ‹but they will still move in вЂ‹response to forces applied to them. вЂ‹In this case, the floor supplied by your foot, вЂ‹knocking over the cup, вЂ‹will cause the cup, and the needle to move, вЂ‹and come to rest on the floor, lifting a book, вЂ‹and put it on a desk does not вЂ‹affect the position of the cup, вЂ‹so they will remain on the floor. вЂ‹It says, yes, вЂ‹there's going to be something on вЂ‹the floor, the cup, and the needle. вЂ‹Now, let's look at the same example, вЂ‹but with chain of thought prompting applied. вЂ‹Here we go with chain of thought prompting. вЂ‹With this one, we've вЂ‹spelled out the reasoning behind each of the examples. вЂ‹We go back to the bike racer, вЂ‹and we say, the total be greater вЂ‹than 200, and so we say, вЂ‹reasoning, each rider will ride вЂ‹30 miles per hour times two hours equals 60 miles. вЂ‹I have four riders. вЂ‹Therefore, the total number of miles вЂ‹ridden by the riders is вЂ‹4 times 60 miles, equals 240 miles. вЂ‹Then answer, yes. вЂ‹This is chain of thought prompting. вЂ‹We're explaining the reasoning behind вЂ‹the examples to the large language model. вЂ‹In this case, we're explaining, вЂ‹we're working out the math, вЂ‹showing our notes, вЂ‹how we got to this answer. вЂ‹Then we do the same thing for the next one, вЂ‹where we're staging a bike race, вЂ‹and we want to figure out вЂ‹how many people have to be staged at a time, вЂ‹in order to start a race every 30 seconds. вЂ‹We give the reasoning, each group takes 47 seconds, вЂ‹plus 67 seconds to be ready to race. вЂ‹I will need you to calculate how many races will вЂ‹need to be run before a group is ready to race. вЂ‹A group will have 114 seconds over вЂ‹thirty-seconds equals 3.8 races вЂ‹run before it is ready to race. вЂ‹I can't have a partial group, вЂ‹so I need to round up to four. вЂ‹I only need four groups stage вЂ‹to be able to race every 30 seconds, вЂ‹so I do not need eight groups. вЂ‹Answer, no. You see, вЂ‹rather than just say, вЂ‹here's the example, here's the answer. вЂ‹We say, here's the answer, вЂ‹here's the reasoning, and then here's the correct answer. вЂ‹So then in this final example with the spaceship, вЂ‹again, we're having the spaceship, there's no gravity. вЂ‹We have a cup with a needle in it knocked on the floor, вЂ‹and then in this example we tell it вЂ‹to provide its reasoning first, вЂ‹and then it's answer. вЂ‹So we're prompting it, вЂ‹and giving it a format that makes it вЂ‹clear we want the reasoning first, вЂ‹and then the answer. вЂ‹What's interesting is we see вЂ‹different reasoning than we saw before, вЂ‹and we get a different answer. вЂ‹If you remember before, we got the answer of yes, вЂ‹the cup and the needle will be on the floor. вЂ‹But if you look down here on this one at the bottom, вЂ‹we can see that it says answer no, вЂ‹because there is no concept of вЂ‹on-the-floor in a zero-gravity environment. вЂ‹If we look at this one, вЂ‹this one is actually giving вЂ‹us a better reasoned answer, in my opinion. вЂ‹Now there's probably different nuances, вЂ‹and I'm not an expert on this. вЂ‹But I think if you don't have gravity, вЂ‹you're not necessarily going to have the cup, вЂ‹and the needle resting on the floor, вЂ‹just because they got knocked off. вЂ‹And so the reasoning is better. вЂ‹In this one, it says, in a spaceship without gravity, вЂ‹objects do not behave as they do on Earth with gravity. вЂ‹When the cup, and the needle is knocked over, the cup, вЂ‹and needle will not fall to вЂ‹the floor as they would on Earth. вЂ‹Instead, they will float in place, вЂ‹or move in the direction of the force applied to them. вЂ‹Therefore in the absence of gravity, вЂ‹there's no concept of objects being on вЂ‹the floors as we stand them on earth. вЂ‹Basically what it's saying is, вЂ‹you might move them, вЂ‹or cause a force to be applied, but it's not, вЂ‹they're not going to just sit there on the floor, вЂ‹because there's no gravity, вЂ‹and so it comes up with the answer, no. вЂ‹You see right here, вЂ‹we're getting a completely different answer вЂ‹out of the large language model, вЂ‹and the difference, is that, вЂ‹one example we're giving it the examples, вЂ‹we're giving it the reasoning behind the examples, вЂ‹and then we're asking it to вЂ‹provide the reasoning, and then the answer, вЂ‹which is this case, and we're saying no, вЂ‹there's nothing on the floor, which is probably вЂ‹a better answer in this case. вЂ‹In the other example, all we're doing is вЂ‹saying, here's the question, вЂ‹here's the answer, here's a question, вЂ‹here's the answer, and we're not вЂ‹giving it the reasoning. вЂ‹Then finally we're saying, here's a question, вЂ‹and it's going to try to produce the answer first, вЂ‹which is what it does. вЂ‹The difference is really only in what it does. вЂ‹Here it's answering first, вЂ‹but it's not explaining its reasoning first. вЂ‹It's reasoning actually isn't quite as good, вЂ‹and it's answer isn't quite as good. вЂ‹Now, spaceship knocking a cup with a needle off on it. вЂ‹This might not apply to you, вЂ‹but it's an interesting example of вЂ‹whereas more nuanced reasoning. вЂ‹If you have a case where you need to think through, вЂ‹and I say, think, very liberally here. вЂ‹But if you need it to try to вЂ‹get better reasoning behind the answer, вЂ‹or a better computation, вЂ‹whatever you want to describe it as, but intuitively, вЂ‹if we thought through the process of getting the answer, вЂ‹we have a good process of breaking down the problem, вЂ‹and going step-by-step to a solution, вЂ‹we're likely to get a better answer out, вЂ‹a better solution out. вЂ‹And so that's what chain of thought prompting is doing. вЂ‹Is we're trying to elicit that. вЂ‹Break the problem down into steps, вЂ‹think about step-by-step, вЂ‹how you're going to solve it, and the вЂ‹way that we get there, вЂ‹the way that we get to do that, вЂ‹is when we give it few-shot examples like we do up here, вЂ‹we explain the reasoning behind the answer, вЂ‹and we will explain the reasoning first. вЂ